Navigate to other release versions of Doxee Platform Resource Explorer

[6.6](https://docs.doxee.com/docs/en/resource-explorer-6-6)

[6.7](https://docs.doxee.com/docs/en/resource-explorer-6-7)

Resource Explorer allows searching for files and folders on a WebDAV server. In a similar way, resources listed in the content pane can be filtered locally.

## Searching
If a server supports searching, a *Search* item will be available in the context menu on folders in the content pane. Selecting this item will open the search dialogue:

![](data:image/png;base64,)

This dialogue shows the search root (i.e. the folder in which the search will be carried out). A check box specifies whether the search should be recursive, i.e. whether sub folders should be searched as well.

In the lower right corner of the dialogue there is a link for switching between the simple and advanced search mode. The remaining content of the dialogue area depends on which mode is selected.

### Simple Search
In the simple search mode, users can search by resource name and file content. If both name and content are specified in a simple search, both criteria must apply for a file to be found. With the radio buttons at the top the search result can be limited to files, folders or both. 

In the field *Resource Name Patterns*, one or more names of files or folder can be specified. In case of multiple names they must be separated by a comma `,`). Names can contain asterisk character `*`) to represent any string or question marks `?`) to represent any single character. Having only an asterisk in the field means that every resource applies. 

If the field *Containing Text* specifies any content, only files in which this text occurrs are found. This field can also contain asterisk symbols representing any string and question marks representing any single character. 

### Advanced Search
In the advanced search, users can specify any combination of search filters which define what resources should be found. On the first time the user switches from the simple to the advanced search, the current criteria of the simple search are translated into a set of search filters in the advanced search. Afterwards any changes on the simple and advanced search are independent. 

Previous search filters can be stored and later recalled by selecting them from the filter presets drop down list. Presets are stored locally as part of the Resource Explorer configuration and can be deleted when they are no longer needed.

Search filters are constructed of one or more conditions, each condition containing the name of a property, an operator and a value. A button to the left of the property can be used to toggle a negation flag for the condition.

If multiple conditions are specified, all of them must be true for a resource to be included in the search results. An *or* element can be added between two sets of conditions to specify that either one set of conditions or the other must be fulfilled for a resource to match.

The *equals* operator `=`) and the *like* operator work the same for all properties and perform a text comparison between the specified value and the actual value of the property on the resource. *Equals* requires an exact match, whereas *like* allows the use of the asterisk character `*`) as a wildcard to match any number of characters.

Comparison operators like '&lt;' and '&gt;' depend on the property type and may compare property values lexigraphically (i.e. as strings) or as numbers, depending on the property and its definition on the server.

The *contains* operator checks whether the value of the specified property contains the provided text.

Clicking *Ok* performs the search and displays the result in the search results dialogue:

![](data:image/png;base64,)

The `Refine search` button can be used to return to the search dialogue and refine the search conditions.

## Filtering
The filter button in the toolbar can be used to define a local filter or to select an existing filter from the list. Creating a custom filter uses a dialogue very similar to the search dialogue described in the previous section:

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Unlike searches, filters are only applied locally. This means that they do not reduce the number of resources returned by the server, but only filter the results displayed in the content pane. On the other hand, switching filters is quick, because no server operations have to be carried out.

Because no server side searches are necessary, filters are available for all host types, including the local file system. However, the available properties and operators may differ from those provided by the server-side search.
